# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: braidwood-academy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] André Laffon de Ladebat was born in Bordeaux, France, the son of commercial shipowner Jacques-Alexandre Laffon de Ladebat.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] He studied in the Netherlands at the Protestant University of Franeker.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] In 1763, returning to France after a stay in England, de Ladebat entered his father's naval armaments business, invested heavily in the development of an "Experimental Farm" in Pessac, and began to deforest the moors of Bordeaux.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] During the same period, he actively participated in the work of the Bordeaux Academy of Sciences as well as the Academy of Painting and Sculpture, of which he was president.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] De Ladebat distinguished himself through his writings on finance, political economy, and the improvement of living conditions.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] Despite his status as a noble, de Ladebat was appointed to the Estates-General in 1789.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] However, as he refused to resign from his post in order to represent the nobility in his *département*, he was removed from office.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] While a member of the executive committee of the Gironde in 1790, he was elected to serve as its deputy to the Legislative Assembly, where he rejoined the moderate Feuillant royalist party.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] He presided over the Finance Committee and assumed the presidency of the Legislative Assembly in June 1792.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] On 20 June 1792, during the riots at the Tuileries Palace, he defended King Louis XVI of France and the royal family, an action that led to his arrest the following December.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] Though released at the beginning of the Convention, de Ladebat was again imprisoned under the Reign of Terror as a suspect because of his connections with the Girondins.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] He escaped the Revolutionary Tribunal thanks to the government's reliance on his credit in order to finance its operations.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] Finally, under the Executive Directory, he was elected a deputy on the Council of Ancients.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] De Ladebat represented a danger to individuals in compromising or corrupt positions of power in need of enormous financial support.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] His personal honesty, thoroughness, and devout Protestantism made him a serious challenge to the Directory.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] Along with Boissy d'Anglais, he unceasingly denounced licentiousness and bureaucratic waste.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] De Ladebat was President of the Council of Ancients at the time of the 18 Fructidor coup against the new moderate majority on the Councils.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] He was later deported to French Guiana with sixteen other deputies.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] He would remain in exile at Sinnamary for over two years with several other deportees, including General Pichegru.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] Of the sixteen deported to Sinnamary, eight died there or while escaping, six escaped successfully, and two were finally recalled to France.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] De Ladebat returned to France in February 1800 after intervention from the First Consul, Napoléon Bonaparte.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] After his return, several *départements* asked him to represent them in the Senate.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] However, he remained suspicious of Bonaparte, who had always blamed him for denouncing previous acts of violence in Italy, and had demanded his dismissal shortly before the events of 18 Fructidor.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] Suspicious of his independence, Bonaparte removed de Ladebat's name from the Senate roles.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] De Ladebat was the only surviving member of the 18 Fructidor plot to leave politics and return to commerce.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] De Ladebat gained widespread recognition for his financial competence and ability after taking over the direction of the *Banque Territoriale* and organizing the final liquidation of the Caisse d'Escompte, a predecessor of the Banque de France.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] He sought to repair the damage done to his finances following his deportation after 18 Fructidor; he reclaimed the remainder of his dispersed or confiscated assets and, notably, obtained compensation for the Sartine, one of his family-owned boats earlier requisitioned for use in the Indies.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] During the Bourbon Restoration, he fell out of favor with the House of Bourbon.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] He also contributed to the establishment of the Caisses d'Epargne and philanthropic institutions.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] In 1818, he became the president of the Protestant Society of Forethought and Mutual Assistance and a member of the Society of Christian Morality.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] In 1821, he was among the founders of the Committee for the Abolition of Slavery, along with Auguste de Staël and Charles de Rémusat.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] Shortly before his death in 1829, he assembled his notes from his deportation to Sinnamary, which would eventually be published by his grandson in 1912 under the title "Journal from my Deportation to French Guiana: Fructidor Year 5; Ventôse Year 8".
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] He was buried at Père Lachaise Cemetery in Paris.
[src:braidwood-academy/andré-daniel-laffon-de-ladebat] His eulogy was delivered by François Guizot, then the President of the Conseil d'État.
[src:braidwood-academy/braidwood-academy] In 1760, merchant Alexander Shirreff asked Thomas Braidwood, who at the time was teaching mathematics in Edinburgh, if he would teach his deaf son, Charles Shirreff.
[src:braidwood-academy/braidwood-academy] Braidwood's second pupil was John Douglas, the son of a doctor in London.
[src:braidwood-academy/braidwood-academy] Aside from teaching deaf children, Braidwood also advertised that he could correct speech impediments and stuttering in hearing pupils.
[src:braidwood-academy/braidwood-academy] At this point in the history of deaf education, there were two competing systems: the French method (manualism) and the German one (oralism), espoused by Abbé de l'Epée and Samuel Heincke respectively.
[src:braidwood-academy/braidwood-academy] Braidwood's methods leaned more towards oralism, developing speech and articulation in his pupils, but there is evidence that he also included signing and the manual alphabet.
[src:braidwood-academy/braidwood-academy] This combined system would come to be known as the English method.
[src:braidwood-academy/braidwood-academy] It is likely that the signing used in instruction followed the structure of spoken English, something that one of Braidwood's successors, Joseph Watson, would seek to change.
[src:braidwood-academy/braidwood-academy] Although Braidwood never documented his own methods, there are several second-hand accounts which describe them.
[src:braidwood-academy/braidwood-academy] A visitor reported pupils learnt first by writing words, understanding their meaning and then lipreading.
[src:braidwood-academy/braidwood-academy] Owing to visits by Johnson, his travelling compantion James Boswell, and the likes of Lord Monboddo, the school's reputation grew beyond Britain and into Europe.
[src:braidwood-academy/braidwood-academy] In 1783 Thomas Braidwood relocated to Hackney, then a village a few miles north of London, already known for its innovative educational establishments such as the Dissenting academies.
[src:braidwood-academy/braidwood-academy] There he re-established the Braidwood Academy for the Deaf and Dumb.
[src:braidwood-academy/braidwood-academy] Braidwood died in 1806 and his family continued to run the school until c.1810.
[src:braidwood-academy/braidwood-academy] By 1814, the original Braidwood Academy in Edinburgh was under the instruction of Robert Kinniburgh, the son of a flax draper, originally from Kirkintulloch, Lanarkshire.
[src:braidwood-academy/braidwood-academy] According to a deaf pupil of his, Alexander Atkinson, prior to becoming an assistant to Thomas Braidwood, Kinniburgh was a minister in Perth.
[src:braidwood-academy/braidwood-academy] He is said to have trained under Joseph Watson in London before returning to run the school in 1813.
[src:braidwood-academy/braidwood-academy] Kinninburgh's sister-in-law Miss Macpherson, also helped in the running of the school.
[src:braidwood-academy/braidwood-academy] At this time, the school had between 40 and 50 students, mostly from across Scotland.
[src:braidwood-academy/braidwood-academy] Around 15 of the pupils were parlour boarders, while the rest had their places funded by charity.
[src:braidwood-academy/braidwood-academy] They were taught a combination of signing and writing with some articulation, the latter also taught by Kinniburgh's wife.
[src:braidwood-academy/braidwood-academy] A formalised style of signing, or "dialect", developed in the school.
[src:braidwood-academy/braidwood-academy] In the spring of 1818, around half the school became ill with typhus fever, leading those infected to be temporarily rehoused on Gilmore Place.
[src:braidwood-academy/braidwood-academy] The area of Edinburgh in which Braidwood Academy was originally located became known as Dumbiedykes - itself named after Braidwood school's 'deaf and dumb' pupils.
[src:braidwood-academy/braidwood-academy] Craigside House was demolished in 1939, though a section of the walls still stands opposite 36 Dumbiedykes Road.
[src:braidwood-academy/braidwood-academy] A commemorative plaque was placed on the site in 2015.
[src:braidwood-academy/braidwood-academy] Sir Walter Scott mentioned Braidwood Academy in his novel *The Heart of Midlothian* (1818).
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] In 2016 the British Deaf Association (BDA) said that, based on official statistics, it believes there are 151,000 people who use BSL in the UK, and 87,000 of these are deaf.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] This figure does not include professional BSL users, interpreters, translators, etc. unless they use BSL at home.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] By contrast, in the 2011 England and Wales Census 15,000 people living in England and Wales reported themselves using BSL as their main language.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] In Northern Ireland, there are about 4,500 users of BSL and 1,500 users of Irish Sign Language, an unrelated sign language.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] A hybrid version, dubbed "Northern Ireland Sign Language", is also used.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] On 18 March 2003 the UK government formally recognised BSL as a language in its own right.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] In 2022, the British Sign Language Act was passed, which legally recognised BSL as a language of England, Wales and Scotland.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] BSL is used in some educational establishments, but is not always the policy for deaf children in some local authority areas.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] As of January 2026, there is no GCSE qualification in British Sign Language available to students, but one is under development in England and planned for Wales.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] The Department for Education began to develop the GCSE in 2019, but the process was delayed due to the Covid-19 pandemic.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] In June 2023, the UK Government launched a consultation for the GCSE, with teaching initially planned to begin in schools from September 2025.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] In 2024, Qualifications Wales suspended development of its GCSE in BSL, setting a new goal to introduce it to schools in Wales in 2027.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] In 2025, Ofqual ran a second consultation to gather feedback on its proposed rules for the qualification in England, releasing the results and its final decisions on the rules in November.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] GCSE exam boards who want to run the qualification in England must next make detailed offers to Ofqual for accreditation based on these regulations.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Many British television channels broadcast programmes with in-vision signing, using BSL, as well as specially made programmes aimed mainly at deaf people such as the BBC's *See Hear* and Channel 4's *VEE-TV*.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] There is also a specially dedicated British Sign Language channel, LumoTV (previously BSL Zone), established in 2008.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] All BBC channels (excluding BBC One and BBC Alba) provide in-vision signing for some of their programmes.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] BBC Two also broadcasts in-vision signed repeats of the main channel's primetime programmes between 00:00 and 05:00 each weekday and early Saturday mornings.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] It also provides signing on weekday mornings between 08:00 and 09:00.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] In 2024, over 10% of Channel 4's programming was signed, including popular shows such as Hollyoaks and Gogglebox.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Published in 1992, the British Sign Language Dictionary was compiled for the British Deaf Association by the Deaf Studies Research Unit at the University of Durham.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] The dictionary was edited by David Brien, assisted by a team composed by Mary Brennan, Clark Denmark, Frances Elton, Liz Scott Gibson, Graham Turner and Dorothy Miles, among others.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] It depicts over 1,800 signs through pictures and diagrams, each sign accompanied by definitions, explanations and usage.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] The signs are ordered not alphabetically, as a dictionary of the English language, but rather according to the phonological characteristics of the language.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] For example, signs that are based on the "fist" handshape come before signs based on the "open hand" handshape.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] The foreword was written by Diana, Princess of Wales, who was the patron of the BDA.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] The British Sign Language Corpus Project, based at the Deafness Cognition and Language Research Centre (University College London), was funded between 2008 and 2011 to provide a video corpus of BSL in four regions (Bristol, Birmingham, London and Manchester).
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] It was succeeded by the BSL SignBank, which moved the BSL Corpus online between 2011 and 2015.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] It also draws on the 1992 BSL Dictionary for its vocabulary.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Certain signs used in Scotland, for example, may not be understood immediately, or not understood at all, by those in Southern England, or vice versa.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Some signs are even more local, occurring only in certain towns or cities (such as the Manchester system of number signs).
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Likewise, some may go in or out of fashion, or evolve over time, just as terms in oral languages do.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Families may have signs unique to them to accommodate for certain situations or to describe an object that may otherwise require fingerspelling.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Although the United Kingdom and the United States share English as the predominant spoken language, British Sign Language is quite distinct from American Sign Language (ASL), having only 31% signs identical, or 44% cognate.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] BSL is also distinct from Irish Sign Language (ISL), which is more closely related to French Sign Language (LSF) and ASL.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] BSL is also distinct from Signed English, a manually coded method expressed to represent the English language.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] The sign languages used in Australia and New Zealand, Auslan and New Zealand Sign Language respectively, evolved largely from 19th century BSL, and all retain the same manual alphabet and grammar and possess similar lexicons.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] The sign language used in Sri Lanka is also closely related to BSL despite the oral language not being English, demonstrating variation in distance between sign languages and spoken ones.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] While private correspondence from William Stokoe hinted at a formal name for the language in 1960, the first usage of the term "British Sign Language" in an academic publication was likely by Aaron Cicourel.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] The earliest known document describing the use of signing in a legal context is dated to c.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] 1324 and mentions John de Orleton, a deaf man assigning his property to a family member.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Published in 1450, the *History of the Syon Monastery at Lisbon and Brentford*, contains descriptions of signs—some of which are still in use.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] The earliest evidence of signing in registry records is from a marriage ceremony between a deaf man, Thomas Tilsye and Ursula Russel on 6 February 1576 at St Martin's Church, now Leicester Cathedral.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Richard Carew's *Survey of Cornwall* (1602) includes a description of Edward Bone, a deaf servant, meeting his deaf friend John Kempe.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Bone had some knowledge of Cornish and was able to lipread, but appeared to prefer signing.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] In particular, *Chirologia* focuses on the meanings of gestures, expressions and body language, and describes signs and gestures in use at the time, some of which resemble signs still in use, while *Philocopus* explores the use of lipreading by deaf people and the possibility of deaf education.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Another writer of the same time, George Dalgarno, recognised that sign language was unrelated to English.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] British Sign Language has evolved, as all languages do, from these origins by modification, invention and importation.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Thomas Braidwood, a teacher from Edinburgh, founded 'Braidwood's Academy for the Deaf and Dumb' in 1760, which is believed to be the first school for deaf children in Britain.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] The school primarily taught oral communication, however there is evidence of 'deaf signing' being used as a teaching method (albeit probably following the structure of English).
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] This *combined system* came to be known as the English method—a sort of midway point between French manualist and German oralist systems, and was the first codification of what would later develop into British Sign Language.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Joseph Watson was trained as a teacher of the deaf under Thomas Braidwood.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] He eventually left in 1792 to become the headmaster of the Asylum for the Deaf and Dumb in Bermondsey where he advocated for 'natural signing'—likely referring to the way deaf children naturally sign, as opposed to following English structure.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] This 'natural signing' is thought to be the precursor to modern BSL.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] In 1815 when Thomas Gallaudet visited England, the Braidwood school refused to teach him their methods unless he paid them.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] So instead, Gallaudet found himself in Paris, having been invited there by the much more accommodating Abbé Sicard.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Gallaudet would eventually take much of the what had learnt in France, back to the United States.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] As a consequence American Sign Language (ASL) today has a 60% similarity to modern French Sign Language and is almost unintelligible to users of British Sign Language.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] By the mid 1800s, sign was the most prominent mode of communication within deaf schools in Britain, and by 1870, there were 22 (often residential) schools found in most major cities around the country.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] The Second International Congress on Education of the Deaf, also known as the Milan Conference, was held in 1880, and proscribed the use of sign language in education; for the best part of a century, sign language was no longer used in the education of deaf children.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Signing was actively discouraged in schools by punishment, and deaf education emphasised teaching deaf children to learn to lip read and finger spell, due to the prevailing belief across Europe established that signing was bad.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Since there was no (or very little) exchange of sign language within educational establishments, signing was preserved through deaf clubs or within families.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Until the 1940s, sign language skills were passed between deaf people without a unified sign language system and many deaf people lived in residential institutions.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] In 1978, the government-issued Warnock Report advocated for the mainstreaming of deaf children which led to the closure of many deaf schools.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] During this time, the Total Communication method was popularised.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] From the 1970s there has been an increasing tolerance for the language, in part due to its recognition as a natural language by linguists.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] In the 1980s, BSL started to be used as language of instruction in schools again, alongside English.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] This decade saw the start of deaf programming on British television.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Deaf scholar and activist Paddy Ladd is credited with getting sign language on television and enabling deaf children to be educated in sign.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] BSL users campaigned to have BSL recognised on an official level.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Police and Criminal Evidence Act 1984 mandates the provision of interpreters.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] In 1999, the Federation of Deaf People (FDP) led a 4000-strong march in London to demand the recognition of BSL as a language.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] This can be considered to mark the first political march by the modern 'British Deaf Community', as an established community.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Let Sign Shine is a campaign started by Norfolk teenager Jade Chapman, whose sister is deaf, to raise awareness of BSL and to petition for BSL to be taught in schools.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] The campaign's petition to Parliament attracted support from over four thousand people.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Chapman won awards for her work including the education award category at the Bernard Matthews Youth Award 2014 for her work in raising awareness of the importance of sign language.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Having been donated £1,000 from the Bernard Matthews Youth Award, Let Sign Shine used this to start a British Sign Language course at Dereham Neatherd High School.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] In 2021, MP Rosie Cooper (a CODA) introduced the British Sign Language Bill to recognise BSL, this time as an official language (not merely its existence as had been done in 2003), which was backed by the government.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] After being dormant from June 2021, the bill began moving through Parliament on 28 January 2022, but during a meeting with stakeholders on 7 February, the language of the bill was revealed to have been pared down substantially, disappointing said stakeholders.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] The British Deaf Association stated that it was 'unhappy' with this removal of language from the bill.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] The British Sign Language Act received royal assent on 28th April 2022.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Linguistics is the study of language, including those like BSL that are not carried by sound.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] In all sign languages the great majority of 'words' (hand gestures) cannot be understood in other sign languages.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] How one language signs a certain number would be different from how another language signs it.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] The way sentences are constructed (syntax) differs from sign language to sign language, just as with different spoken languages.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] British Sign Language is described as a 'spatial language' as it "moves signs in space".
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Like many other sign languages, BSL phonology is defined by elements such as handshape, orientation, location, movement, and non-manual features.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] There are phonological components to sign language that have no meaning alone but work together to create a meaning of a signed word: hand shape, movement, location, orientation and facial expression.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] The meanings of words differ if one of these components is changed.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Signs can be identical in certain components but different in others, giving each a different meaning.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Facial expression falls under the nonmanual feature component of phonology.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] In common with other languages, whether spoken or signed, BSL has its own grammar which govern how phrases are signed.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] One important component of BSL is its use of proforms.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] A proform is "...any form that stands in the place of, or does the job of, some other form." Sentences are composed of two parts, in order: the subject and the predicate.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] The subject is the topic of the sentence, while the predicate is the commentary about the subject.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Question words are generally at the end of a sentence.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Topic-comment means that the topic of the signed conversation is first established, followed by an elaboration of the topic, being the 'comment' component.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] The canonical word order outside of the topic–comment structure is object–subject–verb (OSV), and noun phrases are head-initial.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] The language continues to evolve as older signs such as *alms* and *pawnbroker* have fallen out of use and new signs such as *internet* and *laser* have been coined.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] The evolution of the language and its changing level of acceptance meant that older users tend to use more finger spelling while younger ones make use of a wider range of signs.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] In 2019, over 100 signs for scientific terms, including 'deoxyribonucleotide' and 'deoxyribonucleoside', were added to BSL, after being conceived by Liam Mcmulkin, a deaf graduate of the University of Dundee, who had found finger-spelling such words tiresome, during his degree course.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Similarly, architects Chris Laing and Adolfs Kristapsons developed a project called SignStrokes which developed new signs for the built environment, having not wanted to continuously make new signs for different architectural concepts.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] British Sign Language can be learnt from formal institutions throughout the UK and three examination systems exist.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Courses are provided by community colleges, local centres for deaf people and private organisations.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] A teaching qualification programme was started by the British Deaf Association in 1984 at the University of Durham, called BSL Tutor Training Course, which closed in 1999.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] National awarding organisations run training for BSL teachers.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Each of these organisations has its own curriculum, teaching materials and resources.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] There are two qualification routes: via post-graduate studies, or via National Vocational Qualifications.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Deaf studies undergraduate courses with specific streams for sign language interpreting exist at several British universities; post-graduate level interpreting diplomas are also on offer from universities and one private company.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Course entry requirements vary from no previous knowledge of BSL to NVQ level 6 BSL (or equivalent).
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] The qualification process allows interpreters to register with the National Registers of Communication Professionals with Deaf and Deafblind People (NRCPD), a voluntary regulator.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Registrants are asked to self-certify that they have both cleared a DBS (Disclosure and Barring Service) check and are covered by professional indemnity insurance.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Completing a level 3 BSL language assessment and enrolling on an approved interpreting course allows applications to register as a TSLI (Trainee Sign Language Interpreter).
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] After completing an approved interpreting course, trainees can then apply to achieve RSLI (Registered Sign Language Interpreter) status.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] RSLIs are currently required by NRCPD to log Continuous Professional Development activities.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Post-qualification, specialist training is still considered necessary to work in specific critical domains.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] Communication support workers (CSWs) are professionals who support the communication of deaf students in education at all ages, and deaf people in many areas of work, using British Sign Language and other communication methods such as Sign Supported English.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] The qualifications and experience of CSWs vary: some are fully qualified interpreters, others are not.
[src:braidwood-academy/british-sign-language] There are currently two well-established BSL language learning apps and web platforms: Bright BSL and Lingvano.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] Charles-Michel de l'Épée was born to a wealthy family in Versailles, the seat of political power in what was then the most powerful kingdom of Europe.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] L'Épée then turned his attention toward charitable services for the poor, and, on one foray into the slums of Paris, he had a chance encounter with two young deaf sisters who communicated using a sign language.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] L'Épée decided to dedicate himself to the education of the deaf, and, in 1760, he founded a school.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] Deaf people were banned by the Catholic Church from receiving communion, but in line with emerging philosophical thought of the time, l'Épée came to believe that deaf people were capable of language and concluded that they should be able to receive the sacraments and thus avoid going to hell.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] He began to develop a system of instruction of the French language and religion.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] In the early 1760s, his shelter became the world's first free school for the deaf, open to the public.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] Though L'Épée's original interest was in religious education, his public advocacy and development of a kind of "Signed French" enabled deaf people to legally defend themselves in court for the first time.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] L'Épée died at the beginning of the French Revolution in 1789, and his tomb is in the Church of Saint Roch in Paris.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] He was succeeded by Roch-Ambroise Cucurron Sicard, who became the new head of the school.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] Two years after L'Épée's death, the National Assembly recognised him as a "Benefactor of Humanity" and declared that deaf people had rights according to the Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] In 1791, the Institution Nationale des Sourds-Muets à Paris, which L'Épée had founded, began to receive government funding.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] Jacques and then renamed again to its present name: Institut National de Jeunes Sourds de Paris.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] His methods of education have spread around the world, and l'Épée is seen today as one of the founding fathers of deaf education.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] Although he advised his (hearing) teachers to learn the signs (lexicon) for use in instructing their deaf students, he did not use their language in the classroom.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] Instead, he developed an idiosyncratic gestural system using some of this lexicon, combined with other invented signs to represent all the verb endings, articles, prepositions, and auxiliary verbs of the French language.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] In English, L'Épée's system has been known as "Methodical Signs" and "Old Signed French" but is perhaps better translated by the phrase *systematised signs*.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] While L'Épée's system laid the philosophical groundwork for the later developments of Manually Coded Languages such as Signed English, it differed somewhat in execution.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] For example, the word *croire* ("believe") was signed using five separate signs—four with the meanings "know", "feel", "say", and "not see" and one that marked the word as a verb (Lane, 1980:122).
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] The word *indéchiffrable* ("unintelligible") was also produced with a chain of five signs: interior-understand-possible-adjective-not.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] However, like Manually Coded Languages, L'Épée's system was cumbersome and unnatural to deaf signers.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] A deaf pupil of the school (and later teacher), Laurent Clerc, wrote that the deaf never used the *signes méthodiques* for communication outside the classroom, preferring their own community language (French Sign Language).
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] Although L'Épée reportedly had great success with this educational method, his successes were questioned by critics who thought his students were aping his gestures rather than understanding the meaning.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] At the time of l'Épée's death, there were six schools established around France for deaf children and by 1866, there were fifty-four – all using sign language as the mode of instruction.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] What distinguished L'Épée from educators of the deaf before him, and ensured his place in history, is that he allowed his methods and classrooms to be available to the public and other educators.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] As a result of his openness as much as his successes, his methods would become so influential that their mark is still apparent in deaf education today.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] L'Épée also established teacher-training programmes for foreigners who would take his methods back to their countries and who established numerous deaf schools around the world.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] Laurent Clerc, a deaf pupil of the Paris school, went on to co-found the first school for the deaf in North America and brought with him the sign language that formed the basis of modern American Sign Language (ASL), including the signs of the ASL alphabet.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] Some deaf schools in Germany and the UK that were contemporaries of the Abbé de l'Épée's Paris School used an oralist approach emphasising speech and lip reading, in contrast to his belief in manualism.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] Their methods were closely guarded secrets, and they saw Épée as a rival.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] The oralism vs. manualism debate still rages to this day.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] Oralism is sometimes called the German method, and manualism the French method in reference to those times.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] The Paris school still exists, though it now uses French Sign Language in class rather than Épée's methodical signs.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] Located in rue Saint-Jacques in Paris, it is one of four national deaf schools—the others being in Metz, Chambéry, and Bordeaux.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] Even now, L'Épée is commonly described as the inventor of sign language or as having "taught the deaf to sign".
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] In fact, he was taught to sign by the deaf.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] L'Épée categorised and recorded French signs so they could be taught to others in order to be used in education, especially about the Christian faith.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-michel-de-l-épée] On 24 November 2018, Google Doodle commemorated his 306th birthday.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] Charles Shirreff was born in 1749 to Alexander Shirreff and Agnes Young.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] His last name has, at times, been spelled as Sheriff, Sherrif, Sherriff, or Shirref.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] His father was a wealthy wine merchant of South Leith in Edinburgh.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] At the age of three or four, Shirreff became deaf.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] In 1760, his father approached Thomas Braidwood, who was teaching mathematics in Edinburgh, seeking an education for the boy, then ten years old, in the hope that he could be taught to write.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] Charles became Braidwood's first deaf student; soon afterward, Braidwood founded Braidwood's Academy for the Deaf and Dumb, the first school of its kind in Britain.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] At the age of 18, in August 1769, Shirreff left Braidwood's Academy to study art in London at the Royal Academy Schools.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] He graduated in 1772 with a silver medal, and took up a career as a miniaturist.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] In addition to painting portrait miniatures, Shirreff also produced pastels in his early years.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] Shirreff successfully exhibited oil paintings, pastels, and pencil drawings at the Royal Academy of Arts in 1771, and at the Free Society of Artists from 1770 until 1773.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] Shirreff worked in London after graduating from the Royal Academy, building up a clientele that was mainly theatrical.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] He befriended Caleb Whitefoord, a well-connected Scottish merchant, diplomat, and political satirist who moved in London's wealthiest elite circles, where Shirreff developed advantageous associations with portraitists Sir Joshua Reynolds, George Dance the younger, and Richard Cosway.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] After Shirreff's father had been financially ruined in the Crisis of 1772 by the failure of banking house Neal, James, Fordyce and Down, Shirreff supported the family with his work.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] He applied to go to India in 1778, stating in his application to the East India Company that he had no speech but was able to make himself understood by signs.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] He requested that he be accompanied by his father and his sister Mary to act as interpreters.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] However, his original plan to visit India was abandoned and he remained in England for two more decades.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] Shirreff reportedly taught miniature painting in London to students that included, in 1786–1788, Scottish miniaturist Archibald Robertson.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] Shirreff lived and worked in Bath either from 1791 to 1795, or from c.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] His sitters included actress Sarah Siddons, who wrote of him as more successful in her portrait than any miniature painter she had sat to.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] During that period, he had clients for portraits in common with two other deaf miniaturists in Bath, Sampson Towgood Roch and Richard Crosse.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] In 1795, he renewed his application to go to India, and left England in the *Lord Hawkesbury*, which reached Madras in January 1797.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] He painted in Madras for some years before moving to Calcutta, where he worked on his *Illustrations of Signs*.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] In 1807, he announced it was nearly completed and would be available to subscribers as soon as possible.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] This work has never been traced and is presumed lost in passage from India.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] He returned from India in 1808 or 1809, and again took up residence in London, where he continued to work.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] Shirreff's date of death, often given as c.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] More recent biographies give an earlier year of death, based on probate records showing that Shirreff must have died prior to 5 November 1829, when his will was proved in court.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] On 11 January 1810, Shirreff married Mary Ann Brown, the sister of a fellow artist, at St George's, Hanover Square.
[src:braidwood-academy/charles-shirreff-painter] The couple lived in London, in Fitzroy Square and later in Connaught Square, until his death.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] The **dissenting academies** were schools, colleges and seminaries (often institutions with aspects of all three) run by English Dissenters, that is, Protestants who did not conform to the Church of England.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] They formed a significant part of education in England from the mid-seventeenth to nineteenth centuries.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] After the Uniformity Act 1662, for about two centuries, it was difficult for any but practising members of the Church of England to gain degrees from Cambridge and Oxford, the ancient English universities.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] The University of Oxford, in particular, required – until the Oxford University Act 1854 – a religious test on admission that was comparable to that for joining the Church.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] At the University of Cambridge a statutory test was required to take a bachelor's degree.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] English Dissenters in this context were Nonconformist Protestants who could not in good conscience subscribe (i.e. conform) to the beliefs of the Church of England.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] As they were debarred from taking degrees in the only two English universities, many of them attended the dissenting academies.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] If they could afford it, they completed their education at the universities of Leyden, Utrecht, Glasgow or Edinburgh, the last, particularly, those who were studying medicine or law.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] Many students attending Utrecht were supported by the Presbyterian Fund.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] While the religious reasons mattered most, the geography of university education also was a factor.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] The plans for a Durham College of Oliver Cromwell provided an attempt to break the educational monopoly of Oxbridge, and while it failed because of the political change in 1660, the founder of Rathmell Academy was Richard Frankland, who may have been involved in the Durham College project.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] Almost as soon as dissenting academies began to appear, Frankland was backed by those who wished to see an independent university-standard education available in the north of England.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] Tutors in the academies were initially drawn from the ejected ministers of 1662, who had left the Church of England after the passing of the Uniformity Act, and many of whom had English university degrees.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] After that generation, some tutors did not have those academic credentials to support their reputations, although in many cases other universities, particularly the Scottish institutions that were sympathetic to their Presbyterian views, awarded them honorary doctorates.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] Some of these funds gave their trustees the option of sending young men either to dissenting academies, or to universities abroad.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] An academy, to attract such students, had to offer a course of instruction approved of by the Board for its purposes.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] Funding might be central or local, and there could be doctrinal as well as practical reasons why a given academy was sent students with financial support.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] The Common Fund Board, founded in 1689, gave scholarships to Presbyterian and Congregational candidates for the ministry; its successor, the Presbyterian Fund Board, continued into the middle of the nineteenth century.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] An education at a dissenting academy was not the only option for the Fund Board, since a candidate could also be sponsored at a Scottish university, or elsewhere.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] A gap opened up between the Presbyterians and Congregationalists, as the Independents started to be called, for reasons of doctrine.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] The Independent or Congregational Fund Board was established in 1695 to assist poor ministers, and to give young men who had already received a classical education, the theological and other training preparatory to the Christian ministry.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] In 1730, the King's Head Society was founded by laymen in London who were dissatisfied with the management of the Congregational Fund Board.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] (It took its name from the pub behind the Royal Exchange at which they met).
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] The chief point of objection was the Fund Academies' rule which limited students to those who had already passed through a classical training, including the demanding and lengthy training period required for learning to read Greek and Latin texts.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] The founders of the King's Head Society resolved to found an academy with a six years' course, where young men, without a general classical education, would receive it during the first two years and could then proceed to the usual classical-theological course.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] These academies were funded partly by fees for tuition and lodging, as many of them were run in large houses as boarding establishments.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] Sometimes this funding was organised along the lines of subscribers.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] The Coward Trust from 1743 funded Daventry Academy and a London academy under David Jennings, but was distinct from the ordinary Congregational funding.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] The letter of the law could make the running of a dissenting academy difficult or impossible.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] In the general framework according to which schools must be licensed by the bishop, and ministers (who made up most of the teaching staff) could be in legal trouble for the activities that held together their congregations, some academies simply shut down.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] For a short period (1714 to 1719) the Schism Act 1714 was in force, and aimed precisely to do that; but the troubles of the academies were mostly before this legislation.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] Proceedings in ecclesiastical courts were quite common in the seventeenth century, for example in the case of the tutor Benjamin Robinson.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] The degree of religious toleration in the later half of the seventeenth century varied considerably according to laws passed by Parliament, and also in line with the public mood.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] Some academies, such as that of John Shuttlewood, operated in remote areas of the countryside, and some tutors were required to leave towns where they had previously performed their ministry, for example under the Five Mile Act.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] The Toleration Act 1688 under the reign of William III and Mary II did not mention the dissenters' academies, and proceedings continued against dissenting tutors throughout the 1690s.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] There were also cases of actions against dissenting grammar schools, for example the proceedings against Isaac Gilling in the 1710s.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] In 1723 the *regium donum*, initially a grant to support Irish Presbyterians, became a national subsidy, and subsequently dissenting academies were more generally accepted.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] Several early academies became associated with particular theological positions.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] Richard Frankland of Rathmell Academy and Timothy Jollie of Attercliffe, founders of two of the most celebrated early academies, opposed any departure from Calvinist theology.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] It was rumoured that Jollie even forbade mathematics "as tending to scepticism and infidelity", although several of his students later became extremely proficient in the mathematics.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] Some academies were more broadminded in their teaching methodology, and in their attitudes towards possible methods of church governance.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] Indeed, several students at dissenting academies later became Anglicans.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] The dissenters themselves argued that their academies had stricter discipline than the universities, and were perceived by many to have promoted a more contemporary curriculum based on the practical sciences and modern history.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] In some of the larger academies French and High Dutch (German) were taught.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] The tutors and the students of the dissenting academies contributed in fundamental ways to the development of ideas, notably in the fields of theology, philosophy, literature, and science.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] In the nineteenth century the academies' original purpose to provide a higher education was largely superseded by the founding of the University of London and the provincial universities, which were open to dissenters, and by reform of Oxford and Cambridge.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] Newington Green, in those days a village north of London, had several academies.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] The *ODNB* goes on to describe its advanced and varied curriculum (religion, classics, history, geography, mathematics, natural science, politics, and modern languages) and a well-equipped laboratory, and even "a bowling green for recreation".
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] Lectures were given in English, not Latin, and Daniel Defoe, one of Morton's students, praised its attention to the mother tongue.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] Samuel Wesley, a contemporary of Defoe's, described his teacher "as universal in his learning", although he also attacked the academy on uncertain grounds for promoting king-killing doctrines.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] James Burgh, author of *The Dignity of Human Nature* and *Thoughts on Education*, opened his dissenting academy there in 1750.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] (His widow helped Mary Wollstonecraft establish her school in the village.) Anna Laetitia Barbauld, so closely associated with other leading dissenting academies, chose to spend the latter third of her life in Newington Green.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] Homerton College, Cambridge started life as the dissenting academy Independent College, Homerton, then another village north of London.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] The Tewkesbury Academy, set up by Samuel Jones, had as its students both dissenters such as Samuel Chandler and those who became significant establishment figures such as Archbishop of Canterbury Thomas Secker and Joseph Butler.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] Philip Doddridge was chosen in 1723 to conduct the academy being newly established at Market Harborough.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] It moved many times, and was known as Northampton Academy, Doddridge died in 1751 and the academy continued. and is probably best known as Daventry Academy, which Joseph Priestley attended.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] The academy ended up in London under the name of Coward College, as it was largely supported by the bequest of William Coward who died 1738.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] The college was one of three that amalgamated in 1850 into New College London.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] Hugh Farmer was educated at this college in its earlier days.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] Sheriffhales Academy, Shropshire (1663–1697) was established under John Woodhouse.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] Shrewsbury Academy was started by James Owen in 1702.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] Owen died 1706 and his place was filled by Samuel Benion.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] The academy continued until Benion's death in 1708.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] Warrington Academy led eventually, via Manchester and York, to Harris Manchester College, Oxford.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] In 1757, John Seddon, a young minister in Warrington, established the academy.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] Among the tutors were Joseph Priestley (1761–1767) and Johann Reinhold Forster, a German scholar and naturalist.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] Forster went with Captain Cook in his second voyage round the world.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] Rathmell Academy, which had half a dozen homes, was set up by Richard Frankland in 1670.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] The school moved to Attercliffe, a suburb of Sheffield, Yorkshire, leaving it at the end of July 1689, in consequence of the death of his favourite son, and returning to Rathmell.
[src:braidwood-academy/dissenting-academies] His pupil Timothy Jollie, independent minister at Sheffield, began Attercliffe Academy, on a more restricted principle than Frankland's, apparently excluding mathematics "as tending to scepticism".
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] Donaldson's School was founded in 1851 and was housed in the Donaldson's Hospital Building in West Coates, Edinburgh.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] The school and building were paid for by Sir James Donaldson (1751–1830), who, for a time, was publisher of the *Edinburgh Advertiser*.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] The original benefaction was that there should be 200 boys and 200 girls, with special bursaries for poor children.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] Not all were deaf, although applications on behalf of deaf children were encouraged.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] From 1938, pupils were exclusively deaf.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] This benefaction was similar in style to the benefaction of George Watson, who founded and supported other schools in Edinburgh.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] In 1938, Donaldson's School absorbed the Royal Institute for Deaf and Dumb, Edinburgh, which had been founded in 1824.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] The institute's headquarters in Henderson Row subsequently became part of the Edinburgh Academy.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] The 1851 A-listed Donaldson's Hospital building in Edinburgh was designed by architect William Henry Playfair in the Jacobethan style.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] The building is built round a quadrangle in Tudor style with large corner towers which themselves are each made up of four smaller towers.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] Queen Victoria opened the building in 1850 and is reputed to have said that the building was more impressive than many of her own palaces.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] After more than 150 years in the Playfair building, Donaldson's finally concluded that the building was no longer fit for purpose.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] Many of the rooms were no longer in use, classrooms were unable to use the latest educational technology and the trust could no longer afford to maintain the building.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] In 2003 the school's building was put up for sale and was purchased by Scottish property developer Cala Homes for £22 million, although the school continued to have use of the building until they moved out in 2008.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] In 2015 City and Country, a property developer, submitted plans to develop the Donaldson's Hospital building and the East and West Gatehouses into luxury residential accommodation.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] Cala Homes also submitted a plan to build a new crescent of luxury residential accommodation at the rear of the building.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] A new, purpose-built Donaldson's campus opened at Preston Road (EH49 6HZ) in Linlithgow in January 2008.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] The new campus had facilities for up to 120 pupils.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] As a national Grant Aided Special School supported by the Scottish Government, the central location of the new site made the facilities more accessible to pupils from all over Scotland and the north of England.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] The new Donaldson's School was developed in collaboration with staff, pupils, governors, acousticians and architects.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] It was built with a focus on energy efficiency and the environment.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] Shared teaching, sports and dining facilities formed a hub linking two teaching wings – the primary and secondary schools.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] Both schools were grouped around individual play spaces with links and views across the surrounding area.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] Facilities included a gym, swimming pool, fitness room, dining room, library, and assembly hall as well as an art studio.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] Classrooms, each of which accommodated six pupils, feature soundfield systems and interactive whiteboards.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] Donaldson's Lodge (residential accommodation) had 24 rooms placed in a separate building at the edge of the site in Linlithgow.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] Donaldson's uses British Sign Language, Signed Supported English and spoken English, and caters for children and young people from five to 18 years.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] The curriculum is delivered by an interdisciplinary team of specialist teachers who are supported by specialist learning support assistants and residential care workers, providing round the clock education and care.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] The team includes: specialist teachers; speech and language therapists; a physiotherapist; and an occupational therapist.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] Laura Battles was appointed Principal and chief executive officer of Donaldson's in October 2014.
[src:braidwood-academy/donaldson-s-school] In 2015 she announced that the school had been incurring losses for several years and that the nursery section of the school would close.
[src:braidwood-academy/draper] Drapers were an important trade guild during the medieval period, when the sellers of cloth operated out of drapers' shops.
[src:braidwood-academy/draper] However the original meaning of the term has now largely fallen out of use.
[src:braidwood-academy/draper] In 1724, Jonathan Swift wrote a series of satirical pamphlets in the guise of a draper called the *Drapier's Letters*.
[src:braidwood-academy/draper] A draper is now defined as a highly skilled role within the fashion industry.
[src:braidwood-academy/draper] The term is used within a fashion design or costume design studio for people tasked with creating garments or patterns by draping fabric over a dress form; draping uses a human form to physically position the cloth into a desired pattern.
[src:braidwood-academy/draper] This is an alternative method to drafting, when the garment is initially worked out from measurements on paper.
[src:braidwood-academy/draper] A fashion draper may also be known as a "first hand" because they are often the most skilled creator in the workshop and the "first" to work with the cloth for a garment.
[src:braidwood-academy/draper] However a first hand in a costume studio is often an assistant to the draper.
[src:braidwood-academy/draper] They are responsible for cutting the fabric with the patterns and assisting in costume fittings.
